abstract: Democratic senators had been holding together during the impeachment trial, but a crack appeared.
snippet: Democratic senators had been holding together during the impeachment trial, but a crack appeared.
lead_paragraph: The Senate’s Democrats have held together in remarkable unison since the impeachment trial of President Trump began. On Wednesday, a crack appeared.

abstract: They can ask whatever they want of the House managers and the president’s defense team. But only in writing.
snippet: They can ask whatever they want of the House managers and the president’s defense team. But only in writing.
lead_paragraph: When President Trump’s trial resumes at 1 p.m. Wednesday, senators will finally be allowed to ask whatever they want of House prosecutors and White House lawyers. But only in writing.

abstract: A trade agreement with Mexico and Canada revises Mexico’s labor laws and encourages more auto production in North America.
snippet: A trade agreement with Mexico and Canada revises Mexico’s labor laws and encourages more auto production in North America.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump signed the revised North American Free Trade Agreement into law on Wednesday, fulfilling a campaign promise to rewrite “one of the worst trade deals” in history.

abstract: The leaders of the two parties will seek to highlight favorable points and give their sides a chance to rebut the claims made by their adversaries during opening arguments.
snippet: The leaders of the two parties will seek to highlight favorable points and give their sides a chance to rebut the claims made by their adversaries during opening arguments.
lead_paragraph: The questioning phase is a moment of opportunity — and peril — for both parties, as 100 senators question the House impeachment managers and President Trump’s legal defense team for up to 16 hours over two days.
headline_main: The questioning phase could shape the endgame of the trial.

abstract: President Donald Trump's plan for ending the Israeli-Palestinian conflict paves the way for Israel to annex most or all of its settlements in the occupied West Bank.
snippet: President Donald Trump's plan for ending the Israeli-Palestinian conflict paves the way for Israel to annex most or all of its settlements in the occupied West Bank.
lead_paragraph: JERUSALEM — President Donald Trump's plan for ending the Israeli-Palestinian conflict paves the way for Israel to annex most or all of its settlements in the occupied West Bank.
headline_main: A Look at Israel's Settlements Ahead of Possible Annexation
headline_print_headline: A Look at Israel's Settlements Ahead of Possible Annexation

abstract: The president wrote on Twitter that his former national security adviser was fired was fired because “frankly, if I listened to him, we would be in World War Six by now.”
snippet: The president wrote on Twitter that his former national security adviser was fired was fired because “frankly, if I listened to him, we would be in World War Six by now.”
lead_paragraph: President Trump lashed out at his former national security adviser, John R. Bolton, on Wednesday, saying Mr. Bolton “begged” him for a job that would not require Senate confirmation, and was fired because “frankly, if I listened to him, we would be in World War Six by now.”
headline_main: Trump says Bolton ‘begged’ him for a job.

abstract: Senator Mitch McConnell told a group of Republicans that, by his count, he did not yet have enough votes to block witnesses.
snippet: Senator Mitch McConnell told a group of Republicans that, by his count, he did not yet have enough votes to block witnesses.
lead_paragraph: A vote to consider allowing new witnesses and evidence in the impeachment trial is expected to be held as early as Friday, after senators finish questioning both sides in the case. The result of that vote may be the most consequential factor remaining in the trial.

headline_main: Are Republicans shifting their stance on witnesses?

abstract: The president took to his favorite social media platform just after midnight.
snippet: The president took to his favorite social media platform just after midnight.
lead_paragraph: Just after midnight, President Trump asked a question on Twitter: “Why didn’t John Bolton complain about this ‘nonsense’ a long time ago, when he was very publicly terminated. He said, not that it matters, NOTHING!”
